The question is whether we need to find the most optimal algorithm or brute force is enough.

1. in case of brute force removing digit from `k` position (from the right) actually means performing following transformation with `num`: `num % (10^k) + num / (10^(k+1)) * (10^k)`, examples for 5438:
- `k = 0`: `5438 % 1 + 5438 / 10 * 1 = 0 + 543 = 543`
- `k = 1`: `5438 % 10 + 5438 / 100 * 10 = 8 + 540 = 548`
- `k = 2`: `5438 % 100 + 5438 / 1000 * 100 = 38 + 500 = 538`
- `k = 3`: `5438 % 1000 + 5438 / 10000 * 1000 = 438 + 0 = 438` 

and the corresponding code is:

```java
    public static int maxNum(int num) {
        int max = 0;
        for (int i = 1; i &lt; num; i *= 10) {
            max = Math.max(max, num % i + num / (i * 10) * i);
        }
        return max;
    }
```

2. can we find the digit to remove using &quot;more intellectual&quot; way? Let our number is A&lt;sub&gt;n&lt;/sub&gt;A&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt;...A&lt;sub&gt;k+1&lt;/sub&gt;A&lt;sub&gt;k&lt;/sub&gt;A&lt;sub&gt;k-1&lt;/sub&gt;...A&lt;sub&gt;0&lt;/sub&gt; and `F(k): N -&gt; M` is &quot;remove k&lt;sup&gt;th&lt;/sup&gt; digit operation&quot; operation, then `F(k+1) - F(k)` = A&lt;sub&gt;k&lt;/sub&gt;A&lt;sub&gt;k-1&lt;/sub&gt;...A&lt;sub&gt;0&lt;/sub&gt; - A&lt;sub&gt;k+1&lt;/sub&gt;A&lt;sub&gt;k-1&lt;/sub&gt;...A&lt;sub&gt;0&lt;/sub&gt; = 10&lt;sup&gt;k-1&lt;/sup&gt;(A&lt;sub&gt;k&lt;/sub&gt; - A&lt;sub&gt;k+1&lt;/sub&gt;), so, we prefer to remove A&lt;sub&gt;k+1&lt;/sub&gt; if A&lt;sub&gt;k+1&lt;/sub&gt; &lt; A&lt;sub&gt;k&lt;/sub&gt;, i.e. it is the last digit in the first monotonic non-increasing sequence, and the code is:

```java
    public static int maxNum(int num) {
        int maxPow = 1;
        while (maxPow &lt; num) {
            maxPow *= 10;
        }
        for (int i = maxPow / 10; i &gt;= 10; i /= 10) {
            int digit = num / i % 10;
            int right = num / (i / 10) % 10;
            if (digit &lt; right) {
                return num % i + num / (i * 10) * i;
            }
        }
        return num / 10;
    }
```

